article.headline: Roberson scores career-high 28 to pace Gators
article.linkText: Roberson, Florida wear down Florida State
article.story: GAINESVILLE, Fla. (AP) -- Anthony Roberson got rolling for No. 14 Florida and gave rival Florida State a taste of what to expect when its schedule gets more difficult. Roberson, a sophomore, scored a career-high 28 points Saturday and the Gators wore down the Seminoles with their full-court press in an 87-73 victory. Roberson made seven 3-pointers to help the Gators (9-2) win their fourth straight since dropping two in a row after rising to No. 1 in The Associated Press' poll. The Seminoles (12-2) got a season-high 25 points from Tim Pickett. They saw their hopes of making their first appearance in the poll since January 1998 take a blow, but coach Leonard Hamilton said it was good for his team to face a guy like Roberson before the Atlantic Coast Conference schedule gets into full swing. "In the ACC, you're always running into a guy who's capable of doing it," Hamilton said. "This is typical for us. We had respect for him going into the game, and I thought he raised his game to another level." The Seminoles won their ACC opener last week against Maryland, and go back into the ACC schedule, beginning next Sunday against North Carolina State. Playing its last nonconference game before the SEC season starts, Florida's full-court press slowly deflated Florida State. The teams played back and forth for most of the first 30 minutes. Only when Adrian Moss made an 8-footer did the Gators go ahead 60-50 for their first double-digit lead of the game. Moss' basket was part of a 21-8 Florida run, a stretch of nine minutes during which the Seminoles managed only one field goal. Florida State committed 21 turnovers, and its offense came to a near halt as the second half wore on, its players clearly tired from working so hard to get the ball upcourt against Florida's press. "You could see a good team just quit," Florida center David Lee said. "With 15 minutes left, Pickett and some of those guys turned to me and said, `How are you guys still running up and down the court?" Roberson, meanwhile, took care of the offense. For the second straight game, he had 20 points by halftime. He reached the 20-point mark at the buzzer this time, taking a feed from Matt Walsh and hitting a 3 from the corner for a 39-33 lead. Lee had 18 points, eight rebounds and four assists for Florida. He extended his school-record streak of shots without a miss to 19, over a span of four games and 77 minutes on the floor. The miss came as Lee tried to tip in a teammate's miss, but he grabbed his own miss and stuck it back in, getting fouled and converting a three-point play for a 33-28 lead. Although the Seminoles fell short, they showed their 10-0 start to the season wasn't a fluke. Backup forward Alexander Johnson had 10 points, and the front line of Michael Joiner (seven points, five rebounds) and Anthony Richardson (eight points, five rebounds) banged around effectively with the lighter Gators. Florida's defense helped most in stopping Nate Johnson. Johnson, who came in having made 21 of 36 3-pointers, finished 0-for-2 on Saturday. "We didn't want them to be able to run one, single play," Florida coach Billy Donovan said. "We wanted to make it chaotic, a complete disruption. We wanted them to have to break out of the pattern they like to be able to go make plays." Pickett was the only FSU player who succeeded. He went 6-for-10 from 3-point range and was the only Seminole who made more than one 3. The teams combined to shoot 57 free throws in a bruising game that took a leisurely 2 hours, 28 minutes to complete. This was Florida's sixth straight win over its in-state rival.
